{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Royletron.dev","author":"Darren"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"0420b6f6-6e15-5ccd-81ae-f1e92f732d28","excerpt":"It’s time to get into some gritty technical details about what is going on with\nyour HTML and specifically how does your browser interpret what it sees when it…","html":"<p>It’s time to get into some gritty technical details about what is going on with\nyour HTML and specifically how does your browser interpret what it sees when it\nreads the code that makes up your HTML.</p>\n<h2>Enter the Document!</h2>\n<p>So when your browser downloads your HTML it converts the text into what we call\nthe ‘Document’. Basically this is the ‘live’ version of your running website,\nand this follows a standard pattern we call the ‘Document Object Model’ or DOM\nfor short. The DOM is ‘computer legible’ - i.e. something a computer can\nunderstand - representation of the webpage, and defines how your CSS and\nJavascript will work alongside it. The DOM is in effect a big tree, with\nelements spanning out as branches and leaves of the tree. Consider the following\nHTML:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"html\"><pre class=\"language-html\"><code class=\"language-html\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>body</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n  <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>div</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n    <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>p</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>Hello World<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>p</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n  <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>div</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n  <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>footer</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n    <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>p</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>My amazing footer<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>p</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n  <span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>footer</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span>\n<span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>body</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span></code></pre></div>\n<p>You should already know from the second lesson that HTML ‘tags’ can live inside\nof other ‘parent’ tags, and here we have a <code class=\"language-text\">div</code> and a <code class=\"language-text\">footer</code> inside of the\n<code class=\"language-text\">body</code> tag, and inside each of those is a <code class=\"language-text\">p</code> tag. You will also notice I have\nformatted the text so that each thing that is in a parent is indented by two\nblank spaces - this is very intentional and super good habit to get into. It\nalso shows you the tree, which looks like this:</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/256b73a8dfb49f390874005d6b5d74b9/0297f/fig1.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 66.06129398410897%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Figure 1: DOM Tree\"\n        title=\"Figure 1: DOM Tree\"\n        src=\"/static/256b73a8dfb49f390874005d6b5d74b9/4b3ab/fig1.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/256b73a8dfb49f390874005d6b5d74b9/f8bb1/fig1.jpg 148w,\n/static/256b73a8dfb49f390874005d6b5d74b9/900ac/fig1.jpg 295w,\n/static/256b73a8dfb49f390874005d6b5d74b9/4b3ab/fig1.jpg 590w,\n/static/256b73a8dfb49f390874005d6b5d74b9/0297f/fig1.jpg 881w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Lesson 3 - Document Object Model (DOM)","date":"March 14, 2019"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/lesson-3/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/lesson-2/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Lesson 2 - HTML FTW"}},"next":null}}